WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.460 --> 00:00:03.020
Thermals — let's start with thermals.

2
00:00:03.020 --> 00:00:06.860
We have the sun, as we've discussed,

3
00:00:06.860 --> 00:00:12.180
the engine of the weather — the sun shines on the Earth's surface

4
00:00:12.180 --> 00:00:14.660
and warms the ground.

5
00:00:14.660 --> 00:00:18.820
Accordingly, you get a slightly warmer air layer at the ground.

6
00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:21.890
That's really important for understanding thermals,

7
00:00:21.890 --> 00:00:22.050
when you're flying

8
00:00:22.050 --> 00:00:24.210
or when you have to search for thermals,

9
00:00:24.210 --> 00:00:25.170
you always have to ask yourself:

10
00:00:25.170 --> 00:00:28.450
which air mass, or which ground, is going to heat up more?

11
00:00:28.730 --> 00:00:30.970
Different surfaces warm up differently.

12
00:00:30.970 --> 00:00:33.490
It's always about a temperature difference.

13
00:00:33.490 --> 00:00:36.890
It's not as if you can never fly thermals in winter.

14
00:00:36.890 --> 00:00:39.730
If the meadows are snow-free, for example,

15
00:00:39.730 --> 00:00:43.570
they warm up more than snow-covered fields.

16
00:00:43.570 --> 00:00:46.130
Accordingly, thermals can be found over the woods.

17
00:00:46.130 --> 00:00:49.730
So the temperature difference is always really important.

18
00:00:49.730 --> 00:00:52.130
This also has to do with the albedo effect —

19
00:00:52.130 --> 00:00:57.890
for example, which surface warms up more strongly than another.

20
00:00:57.890 --> 00:01:00.690
A dry ploughed field,

21
00:01:00.690 --> 00:01:03.690
freshly harrowed, warms up more than a green meadow,

22
00:01:03.690 --> 00:01:05.490
which is even better than a wet one.

23
00:01:05.490 --> 00:01:08.450
So you always have to ask: which surface warms up more?

24
00:01:08.450 --> 00:01:10.130
And there are basic rules for this:

25
00:01:10.130 --> 00:01:13.450
if you have a reflective surface, like snow,

26
00:01:13.450 --> 00:01:15.450
it barely warms up at all.

27
00:01:15.450 --> 00:01:19.850
Whereas a black surface, a dark surface,

28
00:01:19.850 --> 00:01:21.690
naturally warms up a lot more,

29
00:01:21.690 --> 00:01:25.430
because it absorbs the sun's rays.

30
00:01:25.430 --> 00:01:27.310
What's also really important

31
00:01:27.310 --> 00:01:31.510
for warming is the angle of incidence.

32
00:01:31.510 --> 00:01:35.270
Ideally the sun hits the surface at a right angle.

33
00:01:35.270 --> 00:01:38.710
Then the surface gets heated much more strongly

34
00:01:38.710 --> 00:01:40.190
than a tilted surface,

35
00:01:40.190 --> 00:01:43.690
where the sun's rays only hit at a shallow angle.

36
00:01:43.690 --> 00:01:48.970
Think for example of the polar regions versus the tropics.

37
00:01:48.970 --> 00:01:52.730
That's also purely down to the angle of incidence of the sun.

38
00:01:52.730 --> 00:01:54.630
Exactly.

39
00:01:54.630 --> 00:01:55.830
Accordingly,

40
00:01:55.830 --> 00:01:58.390
a warm layer of air forms at the ground,

41
00:01:58.390 --> 00:02:01.460
which starts to bubble a bit.

42
00:02:01.460 --> 00:02:04.940
This warm air layer, once the temperature difference is big enough

43
00:02:04.940 --> 00:02:08.500
and it gets released by a small trigger,

44
00:02:08.500 --> 00:02:11.380
it detaches and starts rising.

45
00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:12.820
You can picture it

46
00:02:12.820 --> 00:02:16.060
like a lava lamp — an air mass that stays together,

47
00:02:16.060 --> 00:02:20.420
an air mass with uniform properties.

48
00:02:20.420 --> 00:02:22.940
It's warmer than the surrounding air,

49
00:02:22.940 --> 00:02:24.940
and it rises away.

50
00:02:24.980 --> 00:02:27.780
So we have two air masses with different properties —

51
00:02:27.780 --> 00:02:30.500
the one that matters has a certain temperature,

52
00:02:30.500 --> 00:02:32.220
which we'll touch on briefly later.

53
00:02:32.220 --> 00:02:35.180
And that warmer layer that rises, the bubble,

54
00:02:35.180 --> 00:02:37.740
that's what forms the thermal.

55
00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:40.300
We can also picture a hot-air balloon —

56
00:02:40.300 --> 00:02:43.780
it also rises because it has warmer air inside,

57
00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:45.540
which is less dense.

58
00:02:45.540 --> 00:02:48.380
And so the hot-air balloon rises.

59
00:02:48.380 --> 00:02:52.660
It's the same with a thermal, with this thermal bubble

60
00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:56.140
rising up.

61
00:02:56.140 --> 00:02:59.540
Now, we have a certain air pressure

62
00:02:59.540 --> 00:03:02.380
in our atmosphere,

63
00:03:02.380 --> 00:03:06.020
and lower down the air pressure is higher than in the upper layers.

64
00:03:06.020 --> 00:03:07.460
Let's come back to air pressure.

65
00:03:07.460 --> 00:03:09.980
Now we can tie things together here.

66
00:03:09.980 --> 00:03:13.500
So when a balloon like this rises —

67
00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:16.030
think of those buoyancy bags from diving,

68
00:03:16.030 --> 00:03:19.310
or a weather balloon, you can see it really clearly.

69
00:03:19.310 --> 00:03:20.350
When it's down low,

70
00:03:20.350 --> 00:03:23.990
it has a very small volume of gas inside.

71
00:03:23.990 --> 00:03:26.750
When it rises and the air pressure drops,

72
00:03:26.750 --> 00:03:29.470
the gas can expand more and more.

73
00:03:29.470 --> 00:03:35.430
Accordingly, the volume of the rising air parcel increases.

74
00:03:35.430 --> 00:03:38.870
And from that we can get to the cooling.

75
00:03:38.870 --> 00:03:40.790
When the balloon rises,

76
00:03:40.790 --> 00:03:42.670
there's a decompression,

77
00:03:42.670 --> 00:03:45.470
the pressure on the rising air parcel drops.

78
00:03:45.470 --> 00:03:47.990
It expands, the pressure drops.

79
00:03:47.990 --> 00:03:50.110
And when in an air mass, in a gas,

80
00:03:50.110 --> 00:03:51.910
the overall pressure drops,

81
00:03:51.910 --> 00:03:53.870
the temperature drops too.

82
00:03:53.910 --> 00:03:56.310
We see this really clearly, for example,

83
00:03:56.310 --> 00:03:58.150
with compressed-air canisters —

84
00:03:58.150 --> 00:04:01.230
when you blow air out, it's ice-cold.

85
00:04:01.230 --> 00:04:04.750
That's purely because the compressed air from the compressor

86
00:04:04.750 --> 00:04:08.660
expands very quickly and cools down.

87
00:04:08.660 --> 00:04:11.580
So an air mass that expands cools down.

88
00:04:11.580 --> 00:04:13.300
And the opposite holds too:

89
00:04:13.300 --> 00:04:17.260
if an air mass is compressed, it warms up.

90
00:04:17.260 --> 00:04:20.940
You see this in practice, for example, when you pump up a tyre —

91
00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:22.820
when you inflate a high-pressure tyre,

92
00:04:22.820 --> 00:04:24.460
it gets quite warm.

93
00:04:24.460 --> 00:04:27.500
That's because you've compressed a lot of air into it.

94
00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:30.900
Keep that image in mind — it's really important for various

95
00:04:30.900 --> 00:04:35.020
meteorological phenomena, including thermals.

96
00:04:35.020 --> 00:04:37.460
If you put numbers on it, you can imagine

97
00:04:37.460 --> 00:04:40.500
an air parcel leaving the ground at 20 degrees,

98
00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:43.020
the sun goes up,

99
00:04:43.020 --> 00:04:47.730
and the temperature keeps dropping with altitude.

100
00:04:47.730 --> 00:04:50.490
Exactly — it has to do with the compression

101
00:04:50.490 --> 00:04:53.780
and with rising air masses.

102
00:04:53.780 --> 00:04:56.780
Now, you have to picture this simply:

103
00:04:56.780 --> 00:04:59.980
in the atmosphere we have a certain temperature gradient.

104
00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:02.860
Ideally it gets colder with altitude.

105
00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:06.220
That's just how the air mass behaves — at night, for example.

106
00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:08.220
At night the air mass sits there,

107
00:05:08.220 --> 00:05:11.340
and at the ground it's noticeably warmer than up high on Mount Everest.

108
00:05:11.340 --> 00:05:14.060
It's much colder up there than down here at sea level,

109
00:05:14.060 --> 00:05:15.900
say at the seaside.

110
00:05:15.900 --> 00:05:18.140
And that's the temperature gradient —

111
00:05:18.140 --> 00:05:20.660
there's a profile, a gradient,

112
00:05:20.680 --> 00:05:22.380
because the temperature gradient varies with these inversions

113
00:05:22.380 --> 00:05:23.580
(unclear)

114
00:05:23.580 --> 00:05:25.510
(unclear)

115
00:05:25.510 --> 00:05:34.990
and other processes.

116
00:05:34.990 --> 00:05:36.550
(unclear)

117
00:05:36.550 --> 00:05:37.570
(unclear)

118
00:05:37.570 --> 00:05:49.780
(unclear)

119
00:05:49.780 --> 00:05:52.340
The thermal cap is reached at the point

120
00:05:52.340 --> 00:05:54.340
where the air mass has reached minus 2 degrees.

121
00:05:54.340 --> 00:05:55.660
And the ambient air,

122
00:05:55.660 --> 00:05:57.500
wherever you are on the day,

123
00:05:57.500 --> 00:06:00.340
is at some equilibrium point — it's exactly the same

124
00:06:00.340 --> 00:06:02.140
as the parcel.

125
00:06:02.140 --> 00:06:04.100
Accordingly, the hot-air balloon

126
00:06:04.100 --> 00:06:05.900
no longer has a heat advantage.

127
00:06:05.900 --> 00:06:07.860
And it won't rise any further.

128
00:06:07.860 --> 00:06:10.580
The thermal stops at an equilibrium point.

129
00:06:10.580 --> 00:06:12.920
Exactly.

130
00:06:12.920 --> 00:06:16.290
It has to do with the atmospheric state curve,

131
00:06:16.290 --> 00:06:18.290
with the state of the atmosphere.

132
00:06:18.410 --> 00:06:20.850
The profile actually just describes the atmosphere,

133
00:06:20.850 --> 00:06:26.350
the layering of the air masses as they sit.

134
00:06:26.350 --> 00:06:27.870
The cooling

135
00:06:27.870 --> 00:06:30.070
that takes place here

136
00:06:30.070 --> 00:06:34.310
is also described as an adiabatic process,

137
00:06:34.310 --> 00:06:36.510
or adiabatic cooling.

138
00:06:36.510 --> 00:06:37.910
And there are two kinds.

139
00:06:37.910 --> 00:06:40.990
We'll get to those in a moment with the glider pilot,

140
00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:42.150
and you can

141
00:06:42.150 --> 00:06:45.030
picture how the air mass behaves from its starting state.

142
00:06:45.030 --> 00:06:46.550
Just shown another way,

143
00:06:46.550 --> 00:06:47.990
to imagine

144
00:06:47.990 --> 00:06:49.910
that we're dealing with two different air masses.

145
00:06:49.910 --> 00:06:51.110
That's really important.

146
00:06:51.110 --> 00:06:53.950
There's very little mixing between them.

147
00:06:53.950 --> 00:06:56.790
And especially for the theory exam, what you learn,

148
00:06:56.790 --> 00:06:59.510
that's what's relevant.

149
00:06:59.510 --> 00:07:02.230
There's an advanced meteo course

150
00:07:02.230 --> 00:07:05.270
where you'll learn a lot more about thermal theory.

151
00:07:05.270 --> 00:07:06.870
There are other effects there

152
00:07:06.870 --> 00:07:07.590
that are relevant,

153
00:07:07.590 --> 00:07:13.860
but they go too far for the basic theory course.

154
00:07:13.860 --> 00:07:14.860
Exactly.

155
00:07:14.860 --> 00:07:16.660
So now we have the temperature drop

156
00:07:16.660 --> 00:07:19.380
that the air parcel goes through.

157
00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:22.440
And then a second factor comes in

158
00:07:22.440 --> 00:07:24.840
that's really important for the pilot,

159
00:07:24.840 --> 00:07:27.240
and that's humidity.

160
00:07:27.240 --> 00:07:29.780
In an air parcel —

161
00:07:29.780 --> 00:07:31.340
in this room here too —

162
00:07:31.340 --> 00:07:34.380
we have a mixture including water vapour.

163
00:07:34.380 --> 00:07:37.540
We don't just have oxygen and nitrogen,

164
00:07:37.540 --> 00:07:37.940
but a mixture that includes water vapour.

165
00:07:38.180 --> 00:07:44.320
So in this air parcel there's a certain humidity.

166
00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:44.920
(unclear)

167
00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:48.040
Depending on what kind of air mass it is,

168
00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:49.520
you can picture it

169
00:07:49.620 --> 00:07:53.280
with little blue dots representing water vapour

170
00:07:53.280 --> 00:07:54.340
in there.

171
00:07:54.340 --> 00:07:58.460
And as the air parcel rises

172
00:07:58.460 --> 00:08:00.720
and cools off,

173
00:08:00.720 --> 00:08:03.280
at some point the water vapour

174
00:08:03.280 --> 00:08:05.400
in the air parcel reaches

175
00:08:05.400 --> 00:08:08.300
(unclear)

176
00:08:08.300 --> 00:08:13.430
the change point where the air mass can no longer hold the humidity.

177
00:08:13.430 --> 00:08:16.430
And then

178
00:08:16.430 --> 00:08:19.430
the gaseous water vapour

179
00:08:19.430 --> 00:08:22.430
starts changing into liquid.

180
00:08:22.430 --> 00:08:26.430
Liquid is relative — we usually see it as clouds.

181
00:08:26.430 --> 00:08:28.430
Every bit of fog and every cloud

182
00:08:28.430 --> 00:08:31.430
is essentially nothing other than

183
00:08:31.430 --> 00:08:33.430
water in the air.

184
00:08:33.430 --> 00:08:36.430
Tiny, microscopic water droplets.

185
00:08:36.430 --> 00:08:38.430
You have to say — it's not like rain,

186
00:08:38.430 --> 00:08:40.430
but really, really tiny droplets

187
00:08:40.430 --> 00:08:42.430
that look to us, to the naked eye,

188
00:08:42.430 --> 00:08:44.430
more like gas,

189
00:08:44.430 --> 00:08:47.520
but they're actually water droplets in the air.

190
00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:51.520
And we talk about the condensation level here —

191
00:08:51.520 --> 00:08:53.520
the water vapour simply condenses out.

192
00:08:53.520 --> 00:08:54.520
It comes out of the gas.

193
00:08:54.520 --> 00:08:56.780
Another term you'll come across

194
00:08:56.780 --> 00:08:58.780
is relative humidity,

195
00:08:58.780 --> 00:09:01.390
expressed as a percentage.

196
00:09:01.390 --> 00:09:03.390
At 100% you've reached the point

197
00:09:03.390 --> 00:09:06.390
where the air mass can no longer hold any more moisture.

198
00:09:08.700 --> 00:09:12.260
Exactly.

199
00:09:12.260 --> 00:09:15.260
When the condensation process kicks in,

200
00:09:15.260 --> 00:09:18.260
when the water vapour turns into water,

201
00:09:18.260 --> 00:09:21.260
when it really becomes tiny water droplets,

202
00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:24.260
then physically there's also

203
00:09:24.260 --> 00:09:26.260
a phenomenon —

204
00:09:26.260 --> 00:09:29.260
when it changes from gas to liquid,

205
00:09:29.260 --> 00:09:31.260
heat is released.

206
00:09:31.260 --> 00:09:33.260
A little bit of heat is released.

207
00:09:33.260 --> 00:09:36.260
And likewise when it goes from liquid

208
00:09:36.260 --> 00:09:38.260
to solid,

209
00:09:38.260 --> 00:09:41.260
more heat is released —

210
00:09:41.260 --> 00:09:44.260
a bit of energy is released in the process.

211
00:09:44.260 --> 00:09:47.260
The other way around it's reversed:

212
00:09:47.260 --> 00:09:50.260
when you change states,

213
00:09:50.260 --> 00:09:54.260
from solid to liquid or from liquid to gas,

214
00:09:54.260 --> 00:09:57.260
then heat is consumed.

215
00:09:57.260 --> 00:10:00.960
An important point about the condensation process

216
00:10:00.960 --> 00:10:02.960
is the rough rule of thumb

217
00:10:02.960 --> 00:10:04.960
we can look at here.

218
00:10:04.960 --> 00:10:05.960
And it's important

219
00:10:05.960 --> 00:10:07.960
to understand roughly what's happening.

220
00:10:07.960 --> 00:10:10.670
When the air mass rises,

221
00:10:10.670 --> 00:10:12.670
it cools down.

222
00:10:12.670 --> 00:10:13.670
So as long as,

223
00:10:13.670 --> 00:10:14.670
following the dry adiabat,

224
00:10:14.670 --> 00:10:15.670
it rises

225
00:10:15.670 --> 00:10:16.670
without

226
00:10:16.670 --> 00:10:17.670
any condensation process

227
00:10:17.670 --> 00:10:18.670
happening,

228
00:10:18.670 --> 00:10:19.670
it's quite simple:

229
00:10:19.670 --> 00:10:20.670
it's just 1 degree

230
00:10:20.670 --> 00:10:22.670
per 100 metres.

231
00:10:22.670 --> 00:10:23.670
So as it rises,

232
00:10:23.670 --> 00:10:24.670
it cools by 1 degree

233
00:10:24.670 --> 00:10:26.670
per 100 metres.

234
00:10:26.670 --> 00:10:28.800
Within this thermal bubble.

235
00:10:28.800 --> 00:10:29.800
It's really simple —

236
00:10:29.800 --> 00:10:30.800
an easy number to remember.

237
00:10:30.800 --> 00:10:31.800
Easy to remember.

238
00:10:31.800 --> 00:10:32.800
With the moist adiabat,

239
00:10:32.800 --> 00:10:33.800
the adiabat,

240
00:10:33.800 --> 00:10:34.800
the number is

241
00:10:34.800 --> 00:10:59.800
lower,

242
00:10:59.800 --> 00:11:03.020
(unclear)

243
00:11:03.020 --> 00:11:04.020
(unclear)

244
00:11:04.020 --> 00:11:09.580
because a warm air mass can hold more moisture than a cold one.

245
00:11:09.580 --> 00:11:12.460
A warm air mass holds more moisture,

246
00:11:12.460 --> 00:11:17.460
starts to condense later than a colder air mass, like polar air.

247
00:11:17.460 --> 00:11:21.100
Accordingly the value is a bit higher.

248
00:11:21.100 --> 00:11:26.330
But for us it's enough to know that it's less than one degree.

249
00:11:26.330 --> 00:11:31.390
That's a quick rule of thumb for moist adiabatic cooling.

250
00:11:31.510 --> 00:11:33.910
We can keep the number in mind, and now let's look at

251
00:11:33.910 --> 00:11:38.250
what this means in practice.

252
00:11:38.250 --> 00:11:41.050
Let's take an air mass that's rising.

253
00:11:41.050 --> 00:11:46.090
In this case, dry adiabatic cooling, one degree

254
00:11:46.090 --> 00:11:47.570
per 100 metres.

255
00:11:47.570 --> 00:11:51.130
At a certain point the rising air mass reaches

256
00:11:51.130 --> 00:11:56.570
the condensation level, and the condensation process begins.

257
00:11:56.570 --> 00:12:00.010
From that point the air mass only cools

258
00:12:00.010 --> 00:12:03.890
in this case by 0.65 degrees per 100 metres.

259
00:12:03.890 --> 00:12:06.610
That's the moist adiabatic process.

260
00:12:06.610 --> 00:12:10.130
It continues until at some point

261
00:12:10.130 --> 00:12:15.510
the air parcel has the same temperature as the surrounding air —

262
00:12:15.510 --> 00:12:19.230
those are the two adiabatic cooling processes,

263
00:12:19.230 --> 00:12:25.390
and that's exactly how it works.

264
00:12:25.390 --> 00:12:31.350
Then we have a picture from real flying.

265
00:12:31.350 --> 00:12:32.910
You see the landscape.

266
00:12:32.910 --> 00:12:37.430
Something triggers up front, where the air mass is best released.

267
00:12:37.430 --> 00:12:40.830
Or where the ground heats up the most.

268
00:12:40.830 --> 00:12:43.310
That's perpendicular solar radiation.

269
00:12:43.310 --> 00:12:45.670
There are a few spots that heat up a bit more

270
00:12:45.670 --> 00:12:46.830
than the ground in general.

271
00:12:46.830 --> 00:12:49.390
In this case white surfaces, for instance,

272
00:12:49.390 --> 00:12:52.070
heat up a bit more than the forest.

273
00:12:52.070 --> 00:12:55.750
And here in this scenario my thermal bubble starts up here,

274
00:12:55.750 --> 00:12:57.830
rises and rises and rises.

275
00:12:57.870 --> 00:13:00.150
And at some point in this case it forms

276
00:13:00.150 --> 00:13:01.910
a beautiful cumulus cloud

277
00:13:01.910 --> 00:13:05.070
that marks the thermal bubble.

278
00:13:05.070 --> 00:13:07.550
If you have wind on top of that,

279
00:13:07.550 --> 00:13:10.230
then it's the same as with a balloon rising —

280
00:13:10.230 --> 00:13:14.230
it gets drifted by the wind.

281
00:13:14.230 --> 00:13:16.990
So it's a bit of a puzzle game,

282
00:13:16.990 --> 00:13:20.110
when you get into cross-country flying — flights are always

283
00:13:20.110 --> 00:13:22.070
a bit of piecing things together,

284
00:13:22.070 --> 00:13:23.590
asking where the thermal releases

285
00:13:23.590 --> 00:13:26.630
and where the nice cloud forms.

286
00:13:26.630 --> 00:13:28.590
Another important point —

287
00:13:28.590 --> 00:13:32.440
the thermal, the rising thermal air mass,

288
00:13:32.440 --> 00:13:36.160
doesn't always have to form a cumulus cloud.

289
00:13:36.160 --> 00:13:39.040
It can also be that the temperature advantage

290
00:13:39.040 --> 00:13:43.040
of the thermal bubble, like the balloon, is exhausted —

291
00:13:43.040 --> 00:13:44.640
that things equalise

292
00:13:44.640 --> 00:13:47.800
before the condensation process happens.

293
00:13:47.800 --> 00:13:49.440
Then you have exactly the same thing happening,

294
00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:51.720
the same thermal,

295
00:13:51.720 --> 00:13:53.840
but it stops rising

296
00:13:53.840 --> 00:13:56.200
before condensation occurs.

297
00:13:56.200 --> 00:13:58.480
Accordingly we talk about blue thermals.

298
00:13:58.480 --> 00:14:01.480
That's the term — a blue thermal

299
00:14:01.480 --> 00:14:03.040
is really nothing other than a thermal

300
00:14:03.040 --> 00:14:05.520
that never condensed.

301
00:14:05.520 --> 00:14:09.300
Exactly.

302
00:14:09.300 --> 00:14:10.780
Another term in thermal theory

303
00:14:10.780 --> 00:14:14.740
you'll come across is the lee —

304
00:14:14.740 --> 00:14:20.540
around the lee, sheltered from the wind,

305
00:14:20.540 --> 00:14:23.980
the wind-sheltered side of the mountain.

306
00:14:23.980 --> 00:14:26.020
The side facing away from the wind on the mountains.

307
00:14:26.840 --> 00:14:29.240
We have sun-exposed slopes,

308
00:14:29.240 --> 00:14:33.000
and the surfaces that are at the right angle to the sun

309
00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:35.120
heat up more than the other side.

310
00:14:35.120 --> 00:14:38.520
Accordingly the thermal releases best there.

311
00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:40.640
So we talk about lee thermals,

312
00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:41.440
thermals that typically come up

313
00:14:41.440 --> 00:14:44.520
on the wind-sheltered side.

314
00:14:44.520 --> 00:14:46.280
This of course happens mostly

315
00:14:46.280 --> 00:14:49.600
when you have northerly wind in the Alps for example,

316
00:14:49.600 --> 00:14:52.520
because in the Alps the south-facing sides of the mountains

317
00:14:52.520 --> 00:14:54.000
are always best,

318
00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:55.600
so the side benefits most

319
00:14:55.600 --> 00:14:58.680
when you have a northerly wind or Bise,

320
00:14:58.680 --> 00:15:00.200
the wind comes from the north.

321
00:15:00.200 --> 00:15:05.620
Accordingly the lee thermal is very pronounced.

322
00:15:05.620 --> 00:15:07.860
Lee thermals usually have the characteristic

323
00:15:07.860 --> 00:15:10.060
of being more turbulent.

324
00:15:10.060 --> 00:15:13.460
We've already seen lee or mechanical turbulence.

325
00:15:13.460 --> 00:15:14.900
We'll keep coming back to it.

326
00:15:14.900 --> 00:15:16.980
We have mechanical turbulence

327
00:15:16.980 --> 00:15:19.460
that of course breaks the thermal up.

328
00:15:19.460 --> 00:15:20.860
It's a leeside rotor

329
00:15:20.860 --> 00:15:25.600
that, depending on wind strength, makes the thermal more turbulent.

330
00:15:25.600 --> 00:15:29.160
But mostly the lee thermal is also stronger.

331
00:15:29.160 --> 00:15:33.200
Because the air parcel sheltered in the lee, in the wind-protected area,

332
00:15:33.200 --> 00:15:36.000
has more time to heat up,

333
00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:37.200
it heats up,

334
00:15:37.200 --> 00:15:38.600
absorbs much more heat,

335
00:15:38.600 --> 00:15:41.880
than a windward thermal, for example,

336
00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:45.080
where, if the wind blows the other way,

337
00:15:45.080 --> 00:15:48.680
the air parcel keeps getting blown away.

338
00:15:48.680 --> 00:15:53.000
And the air mass in the wind

339
00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:55.880
doesn't heat up as long as in the lee thermal.

340
00:15:55.880 --> 00:15:58.880
This is something that's more advanced,

341
00:15:58.880 --> 00:16:01.080
but it's good to know — what's important

342
00:16:01.080 --> 00:16:07.400
is just to know that there's such a thing as a lee thermal.

343
00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:09.560
Now let's go back to the temperature curve

344
00:16:09.560 --> 00:16:14.200
we started with — let's go through it again.

345
00:16:14.200 --> 00:16:15.200
It's really important.

346
00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:16.200
There are two air masses.

347
00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:18.200
We're talking about the thermal, the air mass

348
00:16:18.200 --> 00:16:19.320
that rises.

349
00:16:19.320 --> 00:16:22.120
And we're talking about the air mass

350
00:16:22.120 --> 00:16:25.280
that just sits there at night,

351
00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:28.120
which represents the state of the entire air mass

352
00:16:28.120 --> 00:16:30.120
over Switzerland at that moment.

353
00:16:30.120 --> 00:16:32.600
And from this point on

354
00:16:32.600 --> 00:16:34.600
we're really only talking about the air mass,

355
00:16:34.600 --> 00:16:35.600
not the thermal.

356
00:16:35.600 --> 00:16:39.400
There are different scenarios.

357
00:16:39.400 --> 00:16:41.400
Ideally,

358
00:16:41.400 --> 00:16:42.400
or normally,

359
00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:44.400
the warm air mass —

360
00:16:44.400 --> 00:16:45.400
it gets colder with altitude.

361
00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:47.400
So it gets colder the higher you go.

362
00:16:47.400 --> 00:16:49.400
Then we talk about an unstable

363
00:16:49.400 --> 00:16:50.400
layering of the air.

364
00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:52.500
You can picture this:

365
00:16:52.500 --> 00:16:54.500
as the air balloon rises,

366
00:16:54.500 --> 00:16:56.500
it can hold its temperature advantage for a long time,

367
00:16:56.500 --> 00:16:58.500
because the surroundings get colder,

368
00:16:58.500 --> 00:17:00.500
rather than the other way round.

369
00:17:00.500 --> 00:17:02.500
The other case is

370
00:17:02.500 --> 00:17:04.500
a so-called inversion.

371
00:17:04.500 --> 00:17:06.500
These come with special weather situations,

372
00:17:06.500 --> 00:17:08.500
for example with high-pressure influence —

373
00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:10.500
you get inversions,

374
00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:12.500
where the opposite is true,

375
00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:14.500
where it's cold in the valley

376
00:17:14.500 --> 00:17:16.500
and up at the mountain summit

377
00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:17.500
it's very warm.

378
00:17:17.500 --> 00:17:19.500
You know this in winter perhaps,

379
00:17:19.500 --> 00:17:21.500
maybe,

380
00:17:21.500 --> 00:17:23.500
it's cold,

381
00:17:23.500 --> 00:17:25.500
and up at the mountain summit,

382
00:17:25.500 --> 00:17:27.500
skiing, you have the most beautiful weather,

383
00:17:27.500 --> 00:17:29.500
you're almost in a T-shirt.

384
00:17:29.500 --> 00:17:31.500
That's a so-called inversion.

385
00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:33.530
And now picture this:

386
00:17:33.530 --> 00:17:35.850
if a thermal rises through into

387
00:17:35.850 --> 00:17:36.850
an inversion,

388
00:17:36.850 --> 00:17:38.850
where suddenly it gets warmer with altitude,

389
00:17:38.850 --> 00:17:40.850
then we no longer have a temperature advantage.

390
00:17:40.850 --> 00:17:42.850
Then there's a stop,

391
00:17:42.850 --> 00:17:43.850
the air masses simply can't keep rising.

392
00:17:43.850 --> 00:17:47.850
Accordingly we talk about a very stable layering.

393
00:17:47.850 --> 00:17:48.850
That's a stable layering.

394
00:17:48.850 --> 00:17:50.850
So very little thermal activity is to be expected,

395
00:17:50.850 --> 00:17:52.850
very calm air masses,

396
00:17:52.850 --> 00:17:54.850
and you get really milky conditions.

397
00:17:54.850 --> 00:17:56.850
Calm conditions,

398
00:17:56.850 --> 00:17:58.850
beautiful for hike-and-fly and so on,

399
00:17:58.850 --> 00:18:00.850
but not so great for thermal flying.

400
00:18:00.850 --> 00:18:03.140
And then in between you have

401
00:18:03.140 --> 00:18:05.140
a so-called isothermal layer.

402
00:18:05.140 --> 00:18:06.140
That's the one

403
00:18:06.140 --> 00:18:09.270
where the temperature with altitude

404
00:18:09.270 --> 00:18:10.270
stays exactly the same.

405
00:18:10.270 --> 00:18:12.270
So if you have 60 degrees in the valley

406
00:18:12.270 --> 00:18:14.270
and 60 degrees at the summit,

407
00:18:14.270 --> 00:18:16.270
then that's the so-called isothermal,

408
00:18:16.270 --> 00:18:19.270
an unchanging air layer.

409
00:18:19.270 --> 00:18:20.270
Exactly.

410
00:18:20.270 --> 00:18:23.580
The normal state,

411
00:18:23.580 --> 00:18:24.580
though, in the atmosphere,

412
00:18:24.580 --> 00:18:25.580
is definitely

413
00:18:25.580 --> 00:18:26.580
cooling with altitude,

414
00:18:26.580 --> 00:18:27.580
getting colder and colder.

415
00:18:27.580 --> 00:18:32.120
Now there are some exam questions

416
00:18:32.120 --> 00:18:35.150
on these inversions

417
00:18:35.150 --> 00:18:37.150
or unstable stratifications

418
00:18:37.150 --> 00:18:40.150
where you see a temperature gradient written out.

419
00:18:40.150 --> 00:18:43.150
The text might say at 500 m it's 50 degrees,

420
00:18:43.150 --> 00:18:45.150
at 800 m it's 40 degrees —

421
00:18:45.150 --> 00:18:47.150
the gradient is listed like that.

422
00:18:47.150 --> 00:18:49.150
And then you're asked:

423
00:18:49.150 --> 00:18:51.150
OK, where do we have an inversion?

424
00:18:51.150 --> 00:18:53.530
Then you think it through,

425
00:18:53.530 --> 00:18:55.530
you work through the data,

426
00:18:55.530 --> 00:18:57.530
you look at 500 m, and remember.

427
00:18:57.530 --> 00:18:59.530
And remember — an inversion

428
00:18:59.530 --> 00:19:01.530
is the reverse of the air layering.

429
00:19:01.530 --> 00:19:03.530
That means it gets warmer with altitude.

430
00:19:03.530 --> 00:19:05.530
Then you just have to spot the numbers.

431
00:19:05.530 --> 00:19:07.530
In this example,

432
00:19:07.530 --> 00:19:09.530
it would be 50 degrees and at 800 m it's 60 degrees.

433
00:19:09.530 --> 00:19:11.790
That would be an inversion.

434
00:19:11.790 --> 00:19:13.790
The same with a high-altitude inversion —

435
00:19:13.790 --> 00:19:15.790
the same thing happens,

436
00:19:15.790 --> 00:19:17.790
just at higher altitude.

437
00:19:17.790 --> 00:19:19.790
Or an isothermal,

438
00:19:19.790 --> 00:19:21.790
at both altitudes

439
00:19:21.790 --> 00:19:23.790
the same — unchanging air layer.

440
00:19:23.790 --> 00:19:25.110
Exactly.

441
00:19:25.110 --> 00:19:28.200
There's a little exam-rule example.

442
00:19:28.200 --> 00:19:30.200
Then we can move on to the next chapter,

443
00:19:30.200 --> 00:19:33.100
what's important,

444
00:19:33.100 --> 00:19:35.100
we'll do the chapter on

445
00:19:35.100 --> 00:19:37.100
cloud naming,

446
00:19:37.100 --> 00:19:39.100
cloud shapes,

447
00:19:39.100 --> 00:19:41.290
how clouds form and what we need to know.

448
00:19:41.290 --> 00:19:43.290
With clouds it's the case

449
00:19:43.290 --> 00:19:45.290
that we're working with a system

450
00:19:45.290 --> 00:19:47.290
of Latin names,

451
00:19:47.290 --> 00:19:49.290
and it's very complicated

452
00:19:49.290 --> 00:19:50.290
to remember and to memorise.

453
00:19:50.290 --> 00:19:52.290
And altogether it's a real jungle.

454
00:19:52.290 --> 00:19:54.290
So let's try to bring some order to it

455
00:19:54.290 --> 00:19:56.290
and get back to basics.

456
00:19:56.290 --> 00:19:59.800
For cloud naming,

457
00:19:59.800 --> 00:20:02.120
in my head,

458
00:20:02.120 --> 00:20:04.120
I picture a two-by-three grid,

459
00:20:04.120 --> 00:20:06.120
and maybe also a separate

460
00:20:06.120 --> 00:20:08.120
box for special clouds

461
00:20:08.120 --> 00:20:10.120
that don't fit into the grid.

462
00:20:10.120 --> 00:20:12.120
But the two-by-three grid is a good starting point.

463
00:20:13.960 --> 00:20:14.960
And fundamentally

464
00:20:14.960 --> 00:20:16.440
there are two main types

465
00:20:16.440 --> 00:20:18.440
of cloud.

466
00:20:18.440 --> 00:20:20.440
One is a cumulus cloud,

467
00:20:20.440 --> 00:20:22.440
a cumulus,

468
00:20:22.440 --> 00:20:24.440
a clumping cloud,

469
00:20:24.440 --> 00:20:26.440
a build-up — a gathering of moisture.

470
00:20:26.440 --> 00:20:28.440
Those are heap-clouds —

471
00:20:28.440 --> 00:20:30.440
they're called heap-clouds,

472
00:20:30.440 --> 00:20:31.440
all the ones

473
00:20:31.440 --> 00:20:33.440
with 'cumulus' in the name,

474
00:20:33.440 --> 00:20:34.440
and then there's stratus,

475
00:20:34.440 --> 00:20:36.440
which is a layer cloud.

476
00:20:36.440 --> 00:20:38.440
Anything like, for example,

477
00:20:38.440 --> 00:20:40.440
fog — that's a real layer cloud.

478
00:20:40.440 --> 00:20:42.440
Anything that lies nicely horizontally

479
00:20:42.440 --> 00:20:45.430
in cloud fields.

480
00:20:45.430 --> 00:20:47.430
These two cloud types,

481
00:20:47.430 --> 00:20:49.430
they differ above all,

482
00:21:11.950 --> 00:21:13.950
they form above all,

483
00:21:13.950 --> 00:21:15.950
when very strong vertical air-mass exchange takes place.

484
00:21:16.950 --> 00:21:18.950
It's a layer cloud,

485
00:21:18.950 --> 00:21:20.950
where everything just sits.

486
00:21:20.950 --> 00:21:23.880
Just something for understanding

487
00:21:23.880 --> 00:21:25.880
what happens there,

488
00:21:25.880 --> 00:21:27.880
with the two cloud types.

489
00:21:27.880 --> 00:21:29.880
Then onto the storey,

490
00:21:29.880 --> 00:21:31.880
the different altitudes of the clouds,

491
00:21:31.880 --> 00:21:33.880
we have cirrus clouds,

492
00:21:33.880 --> 00:21:35.880
cirrus stands for ice crystal.

493
00:21:35.880 --> 00:21:37.880
That's a very high-altitude layer,

494
00:21:37.880 --> 00:21:41.420
clouds made of ice crystals.

495
00:21:41.420 --> 00:21:43.420
Then we have the alto

496
00:21:43.420 --> 00:21:44.420
storey.

497
00:21:44.420 --> 00:21:46.420
That's the high cloud layers,

498
00:21:47.420 --> 00:22:04.630
and then we have

499
00:22:04.630 --> 00:22:06.870
the altitudes are always relative,

500
00:22:06.870 --> 00:22:08.870
we've said this a few times.

501
00:22:08.870 --> 00:22:10.870
We're talking about 3 km to 8 km.

502
00:22:10.870 --> 00:22:12.870
That's not a fixed altitude.

503
00:22:12.870 --> 00:22:13.870
But what's important is,

504
00:22:45.380 --> 00:22:47.380
that these are the cloud names,

505
00:22:47.380 --> 00:22:49.860
then we have the altocumulus

506
00:22:49.860 --> 00:22:51.860
and the altostratus,

507
00:22:51.860 --> 00:22:53.860
lower the cumulus and stratus.

508
00:22:53.860 --> 00:22:55.860
Those are just the basic forms.

509
00:22:55.860 --> 00:22:56.860
What's also important —

510
00:22:56.860 --> 00:22:58.860
cumulus and altocumulus

511
00:22:58.860 --> 00:23:00.860
differ mainly in that

512
00:23:00.860 --> 00:23:02.860
cumulus is driven by the sun.

513
00:23:02.860 --> 00:23:04.860
It's really a thermal updraft,

514
00:23:04.860 --> 00:23:06.860
as we just discussed.

515
00:23:06.860 --> 00:23:07.860
And altocumulus,

516
00:23:07.860 --> 00:23:09.860
they don't need any sun trigger,

517
00:23:09.860 --> 00:23:10.860
that happens.

518
00:23:10.860 --> 00:23:11.860
There we simply have,

519
00:23:11.860 --> 00:23:13.860
when a cold mass pushes into the air,

520
00:23:13.860 --> 00:23:15.860
it gets lifted and forms cumulus-like clouds.

521
00:23:15.860 --> 00:23:18.020
Everything on the left side

522
00:23:18.020 --> 00:23:20.020
is with an unstable air layering.

523
00:23:20.020 --> 00:23:22.020
The air rises well,

524
00:23:22.020 --> 00:23:24.020
we're back to unstable-stable.

525
00:23:24.020 --> 00:23:26.500
And everything on the right side,

526
00:23:26.500 --> 00:23:29.500
if you have a stable air layer pushing into the air,

527
00:23:29.500 --> 00:23:31.500
then it doesn't rise much.

528
00:23:31.500 --> 00:23:34.500
And if you hit an inversion too,

529
00:23:34.500 --> 00:23:35.500
you hit it,

530
00:23:35.500 --> 00:23:37.500
then those are the two cloud types

531
00:23:37.500 --> 00:23:39.500
that come together

532
00:23:39.500 --> 00:23:41.500
from both behaviours.

533
00:23:41.500 --> 00:23:42.500
It's very easy to recognise,

534
00:23:42.500 --> 00:23:44.500
from the Latin names

535
00:23:44.500 --> 00:23:45.500
in the grid.

536
00:23:45.500 --> 00:23:46.500
Now we'll take

537
00:23:46.500 --> 00:23:48.500
a few special clouds —

538
00:23:48.500 --> 00:23:50.500
we have a few special boxes too.

539
00:23:50.500 --> 00:23:53.240
The first cloud,

540
00:23:53.240 --> 00:23:54.240
in the stratus range,

541
00:23:54.240 --> 00:23:56.240
is the so-called nimbostratus,

542
00:23:56.240 --> 00:23:58.240
nimbo-strat for rain.

543
00:23:58.240 --> 00:24:00.240
Accordingly, a layer cloud

544
00:24:00.240 --> 00:24:02.240
that really rains itself out —

545
00:24:02.240 --> 00:24:04.240
we often have it with a warm front for example,

546
00:24:04.240 --> 00:24:06.240
or in a low-pressure system,

547
00:24:06.240 --> 00:24:08.240
in a situation where it's just pouring,

548
00:24:08.240 --> 00:24:09.240
where it's just raining,

549
00:24:09.240 --> 00:24:10.240
with that grey soup

550
00:24:10.240 --> 00:24:11.240
hanging over you,

551
00:24:11.240 --> 00:24:12.240
and the rain pouring out of it.

552
00:24:12.240 --> 00:24:14.240
That's typically a nimbostratus,

553
00:24:14.240 --> 00:24:15.240
so,

554
00:24:15.240 --> 00:24:17.160
tucked in there.

555
00:24:17.160 --> 00:24:19.160
(unclear)

556
00:24:19.160 --> 00:24:21.160
(unclear)

557
00:24:21.160 --> 00:24:23.160
(unclear)

558
00:24:23.160 --> 00:24:24.160
(unclear)

559
00:24:24.160 --> 00:24:41.160
(unclear)

560
00:24:41.160 --> 00:24:42.160
(unclear)

561
00:24:42.160 --> 00:24:47.230
What flashes and thunders and rains, and is really dangerous for us, is in this sense the cumulonimbus.

562
00:24:47.230 --> 00:24:53.230
The ones that really go from the lower storey all the way up to the tropopause.

563
00:24:53.230 --> 00:24:56.230
We'll come back to those in a moment.

564
00:24:56.230 --> 00:25:00.230
Logically there are many more special clouds and detailed names,

565
00:25:00.230 --> 00:25:05.230
but for you now, for normal flying,

566
00:25:05.230 --> 00:25:07.230
the rest is really what's relevant.

567
00:25:08.230 --> 00:25:10.230
If you want to dig further, look it up.

568
00:25:10.230 --> 00:25:14.640
On the topic of clouds, there's also cloud cover,

569
00:25:14.640 --> 00:25:18.640
which you'll read again and again in weather reports or for gliding,

570
00:25:18.640 --> 00:25:21.640
weather reports, etc.

571
00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:23.640
It's always expressed in eighths.

572
00:25:23.640 --> 00:25:27.680
So eight-eighths cover is a closed cloud cover.

573
00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:30.680
You can't see any blue sky, it's completely covered.

574
00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:34.680
Zero eighths means logically no clouds — maybe just blue thermals,

575
00:25:34.680 --> 00:25:37.680
perhaps with a few wisps.

576
00:25:37.680 --> 00:25:39.680
We always come back to nuances.

577
00:25:39.680 --> 00:25:46.680
Accordingly you get different sub-grades — two-eighths means two-eighths of the sky is covered,

578
00:25:46.680 --> 00:25:51.120
and the other six-eighths are blue and clear.

579
00:25:51.120 --> 00:25:53.120
And four-eighths is half-covered.

580
00:25:53.120 --> 00:25:57.120
Four-eighths is a pretty nice cloud cover for thermal flying.

581
00:25:57.120 --> 00:26:01.120
Something between three and four eighths, when you've got nice cumulus clouds.

582
00:26:01.120 --> 00:26:08.120
And there's still enough blue sky for the sun to heat the ground, for nice weather, for thermals to develop.

583
00:26:08.120 --> 00:26:10.120
That's it for cloud cover.

584
00:26:10.120 --> 00:26:17.330
Then a really exciting cloud is the lenticularis,

585
00:26:17.330 --> 00:26:21.330
fairly special, one most pilots know or come across quickly.

586
00:26:21.330 --> 00:26:27.970
Lenticularis needs two or three ingredients: it needs a mountain range.

587
00:26:27.970 --> 00:26:32.420
The other is very strong wind — so lenticularis clouds

588
00:26:32.420 --> 00:26:35.480
always indicate very, very strong winds aloft.

589
00:26:35.480 --> 00:26:40.900
And of course we need a bit of humidity for them to form.

590
00:26:40.900 --> 00:26:47.900
It usually happens directly above mountain summits, or on the lee side of a range.

591
00:26:47.900 --> 00:26:53.090
Because rotors form there — the air moves in a wave,

592
00:26:53.090 --> 00:26:57.090
what we call a standing wave, because it always moves up the wave,

593
00:26:57.090 --> 00:27:00.090
the air rises, forms a wave shape,

594
00:27:00.090 --> 00:27:04.090
then sinks again, stops condensing, and you get wave clouds.

595
00:27:04.090 --> 00:27:08.020
What's important for us to know for flying

596
00:27:08.020 --> 00:27:10.080
is that this means very strong winds.

597
00:27:10.080 --> 00:27:13.080
But because the mountain stays in the same place,

598
00:27:13.080 --> 00:27:14.080
it stays.

599
00:27:14.080 --> 00:27:18.080
And the wave, the standing wave, more or less always stays in the same place,

600
00:27:18.080 --> 00:27:20.080
the cloud stays stationary.

601
00:27:20.080 --> 00:27:26.080
So the air parcel rises, sinks again and stops condensing.

602
00:27:27.080 --> 00:27:30.080
And accordingly we get clouds that look

603
00:27:30.080 --> 00:27:32.080
as if humidity is supplied to them.

604
00:27:32.080 --> 00:27:34.080
But the cloud always stays in the same place.

605
00:27:34.080 --> 00:27:36.080
That's an important thing.

606
00:27:36.080 --> 00:27:39.080
So just because a cloud stays still doesn't mean there's no wind.

607
00:27:39.080 --> 00:27:40.240
Of course.

608
00:27:40.240 --> 00:27:43.240
But the cloud shapes are very striking.

609
00:27:43.240 --> 00:27:46.240
And for all paraglider pilots, it's always a bit of an alarm sign

610
00:27:46.240 --> 00:27:48.240
when you see a lenticularis cloud.

611
00:27:48.240 --> 00:27:50.910
Exactly.

612
00:27:50.910 --> 00:27:55.910
The most important topic for paraglider pilots is always thunderstorms.

613
00:27:55.910 --> 00:28:00.550
With thunderstorms, the thing is, a thunderstorm is really nothing other than

614
00:28:00.550 --> 00:28:05.550
a cumulus cloud that has grown and grown and grown and grown.

615
00:28:05.550 --> 00:28:09.770
It's really one huge mega-thermal cloud.

616
00:28:09.770 --> 00:28:11.770
And that's what makes it so dangerous for us,

617
00:28:11.770 --> 00:28:14.770
because when we fly thermals, we fly exactly on those days

618
00:28:14.770 --> 00:28:18.930
when storms can develop or when there may be storms.

619
00:28:18.930 --> 00:28:20.930
And so we really need to know clearly

620
00:28:20.930 --> 00:28:23.930
what the dangers of thunderstorms are, and we need to be careful

621
00:28:23.930 --> 00:28:25.930
when the thunderclouds naturally get bigger.

622
00:28:27.960 --> 00:28:29.960
It usually starts in the morning,

623
00:28:29.960 --> 00:28:30.960
the first cumulus clouds,

624
00:28:30.960 --> 00:28:32.960
we go flying around eleven,

625
00:28:32.960 --> 00:28:34.960
everything beautiful, wonderful flying conditions.

626
00:28:34.960 --> 00:28:40.470
And then the thunderclouds, or the cumulus clouds, really get a bit bigger.

627
00:28:40.470 --> 00:28:42.470
And of course they develop with the sun.

628
00:28:42.470 --> 00:28:45.790
We always need the engine of the sun.

629
00:28:45.790 --> 00:28:47.790
And the engine slowly starts up like an ignition,

630
00:28:47.790 --> 00:28:50.790
let's say, like an engine that's just being started up.

631
00:28:50.790 --> 00:28:52.790
And we have to slowly start being careful,

632
00:28:52.790 --> 00:28:54.790
when the cumulus clouds, the cloud bases,

633
00:28:54.790 --> 00:28:56.790
start joining together.

634
00:28:57.790 --> 00:28:59.950
We had small clouds.

635
00:28:59.950 --> 00:29:02.950
And for example, two clouds merge.

636
00:29:02.950 --> 00:29:04.950
But now we're talking about large surfaces.

637
00:29:04.950 --> 00:29:06.950
It's no longer little puffies,

638
00:29:06.950 --> 00:29:08.950
but really large clouds

639
00:29:08.950 --> 00:29:10.950
that have several kilometres' extent.

640
00:29:10.950 --> 00:29:12.950
And as soon as the cloud bases,

641
00:29:26.950 --> 00:29:28.950
the water droplets,

642
00:29:28.950 --> 00:29:30.950
and eventually, when the cloud gets really tall,

643
00:29:30.950 --> 00:29:32.950
we can block out the sun's rays.

644
00:29:32.950 --> 00:29:33.950
And that's the point

645
00:29:33.950 --> 00:29:35.950
when the cloud slowly starts getting dark.

646
00:29:35.950 --> 00:29:39.680
The shadow, underneath, beneath the base, also gets dark.

647
00:29:39.680 --> 00:29:41.680
And that's the point

648
00:29:41.680 --> 00:29:43.680
when you have to start paying attention.

649
00:29:43.680 --> 00:29:45.680
And of course it has a lot to do with experience —

650
00:29:45.680 --> 00:29:46.680
how long do we still fly,

651
00:29:46.680 --> 00:29:48.680
how long do we stay under this cloud?

652
00:29:48.680 --> 00:29:50.680
Is it already a big cloud or not?

653
00:29:50.680 --> 00:29:52.680
That's really in the area

654
00:29:52.680 --> 00:29:54.680
where as you progress

655
00:29:54.680 --> 00:29:55.680
you learn more and more,

656
00:29:55.680 --> 00:29:57.680
because it really comes down to flying experience.

657
00:29:57.680 --> 00:29:59.680
And one basic rule is:

658
00:29:59.680 --> 00:30:01.680
when it starts lifting everywhere,

659
00:30:01.680 --> 00:30:03.680
it's always hard

660
00:30:03.680 --> 00:30:06.680
to find the thermal, to find the local updrafts.

661
00:30:06.680 --> 00:30:08.680
And then it starts lifting everywhere,

662
00:30:08.680 --> 00:30:09.680
all over the valley,

663
00:30:09.680 --> 00:30:10.680
no falling air.

664
00:30:10.680 --> 00:30:12.680
It rises and the cloud grows,

665
00:30:12.680 --> 00:30:14.680
and that's when you really need to be careful.

666
00:30:14.680 --> 00:30:17.680
Then the thunder

667
00:30:17.680 --> 00:30:19.680
from the storm slowly starts.

668
00:30:19.680 --> 00:30:22.320
And yes, if

669
00:30:22.320 --> 00:30:24.320
they keep merging more and more,

670
00:30:24.320 --> 00:30:25.320
they come together,

671
00:30:25.320 --> 00:30:27.320
they get higher and higher.

672
00:30:27.320 --> 00:30:29.320
And it doesn't really need any more power

673
00:30:29.320 --> 00:30:30.320
from the sun,

674
00:30:30.320 --> 00:30:31.320
because the storm starts of course

675
00:30:31.320 --> 00:30:32.320
to spin a lot more.

676
00:30:32.320 --> 00:30:34.320
Because warm air rises,

677
00:30:34.320 --> 00:30:35.320
cools off,

678
00:30:35.320 --> 00:30:36.320
cools further,

679
00:30:36.320 --> 00:30:37.320
and then, when it's cold,

680
00:30:37.320 --> 00:30:38.320
the air sinks,

681
00:30:38.320 --> 00:30:39.040
the warm air

682
00:30:39.040 --> 00:30:41.320
rises even faster, and you get a chain reaction,

683
00:30:41.320 --> 00:30:42.320
a turbo,

684
00:30:42.320 --> 00:30:43.320
that starts running.

685
00:30:43.320 --> 00:30:45.320
And the cloud doesn't always grow,

686
00:30:45.320 --> 00:30:48.320
but often grows up to the tropopause.

687
00:30:48.320 --> 00:30:51.320
And then you get the beautiful anvil shapes of the cloud.

688
00:30:51.320 --> 00:30:53.320
That's when the thundercloud

689
00:30:53.320 --> 00:30:54.320
hits the top,

690
00:30:54.320 --> 00:30:55.320
the tropopause —

691
00:30:55.320 --> 00:30:56.320
you can imagine it

692
00:30:56.320 --> 00:30:59.320
like a plexiglass lid above the cloud,

693
00:30:59.320 --> 00:31:01.320
and then it can only spread sideways

694
00:31:01.320 --> 00:31:03.320
and forms the anvil.

695
00:31:03.320 --> 00:31:05.410
And in this phase,

696
00:31:05.410 --> 00:31:07.410
when it's really developed,

697
00:31:07.410 --> 00:31:09.410
there's a lot of friction

698
00:31:09.410 --> 00:31:10.410
in the air masses

699
00:31:10.410 --> 00:31:11.410
as they rise and fall.

700
00:31:11.410 --> 00:31:13.410
And in this process

701
00:31:13.410 --> 00:31:14.410
you get lightning sometimes

702
00:31:14.410 --> 00:31:16.410
and above all there's precipitation.

703
00:31:16.410 --> 00:31:17.410
Hmm.

704
00:31:17.410 --> 00:31:19.410
More on that.

705
00:31:19.410 --> 00:31:20.410
And something

706
00:31:20.410 --> 00:31:22.410
I really want to drum in

707
00:31:22.410 --> 00:31:23.410
is:

708
00:31:23.410 --> 00:31:24.410
everyone is scared of a thunderstorm

709
00:31:24.410 --> 00:31:25.410
when they're under it,

710
00:31:25.410 --> 00:31:26.410
and you know the stories

711
00:31:26.410 --> 00:31:27.410
that should never need to be told,

712
00:31:27.410 --> 00:31:28.410
about the pilots and so on.

713
00:31:28.410 --> 00:31:30.410
The updraft is also extreme,

714
00:31:30.410 --> 00:31:32.410
so we really need to be careful.

715
00:31:32.410 --> 00:31:33.410
Hmm.

716
00:31:33.410 --> 00:31:35.410
But what we have to be even more careful of

717
00:31:35.410 --> 00:31:36.410
is the danger

718
00:31:36.410 --> 00:31:38.410
from the outflow of the thunderstorm.

719
00:31:38.410 --> 00:31:39.480
The air mass

720
00:31:39.480 --> 00:31:41.480
that rose and got extremely cooled off,

721
00:31:41.480 --> 00:31:44.510
up at 13,000 metres,

722
00:31:44.510 --> 00:31:46.510
cools at some point,

723
00:31:46.510 --> 00:31:47.510
and it's like a bucket

724
00:31:47.510 --> 00:31:49.510
that gets emptied out.

725
00:31:49.510 --> 00:31:50.510
And accordingly

726
00:31:51.670 --> 00:32:10.670
it empties out, the warm,

727
00:32:10.670 --> 00:32:11.670
the cold air comes out,

728
00:32:11.670 --> 00:32:13.670
the precipitation,

729
00:32:13.670 --> 00:32:14.670
the released cold.

730
00:32:14.670 --> 00:32:16.760
It hits us and

731
00:32:16.760 --> 00:32:17.760
we don't want to be in it,

732
00:32:17.760 --> 00:32:19.760
and these are real examples.

733
00:32:20.760 --> 00:32:23.760
And it's very, very unpleasant.

734
00:32:23.760 --> 00:32:25.760
This cold air, the outflow,

735
00:32:25.760 --> 00:32:26.760
can in some circumstances,

736
00:32:26.760 --> 00:32:28.760
when the next thunderstorm triggers,

737
00:32:28.760 --> 00:32:29.760
where again warm air masses,

738
00:32:29.760 --> 00:32:31.760
say in the valley floor lying there,

739
00:32:31.760 --> 00:32:33.760
cold air comes down,

740
00:32:33.760 --> 00:32:34.760
the warm rises further

741
00:32:34.760 --> 00:32:37.760
and you get the next storm cell

742
00:32:37.760 --> 00:32:39.760
and even more storms.

743
00:32:39.760 --> 00:32:41.760
So we really need to be careful

744
00:32:41.760 --> 00:32:43.760
of these cold outflows from thunderstorms.

745
00:32:43.760 --> 00:32:45.760
It's almost as dangerous as being under them.

746
00:32:45.760 --> 00:32:47.760
In any case it's dangerous,

747
00:32:47.760 --> 00:32:49.760
but cold outflows are something

748
00:32:49.760 --> 00:32:51.760
that unfortunately many pilots underestimate,

749
00:32:51.760 --> 00:32:52.760
again and again.

750
00:32:52.760 --> 00:32:55.140
Now you see,

751
00:32:55.140 --> 00:32:56.140
if you see one here too,

752
00:32:56.140 --> 00:32:57.140
looking like that,

753
00:32:57.140 --> 00:32:59.140
if you of course don't want to be flying out

754
00:32:59.140 --> 00:33:00.140
with a cloud like that,

755
00:33:00.140 --> 00:33:02.140
then it's all over anyway.

756
00:33:02.140 --> 00:33:04.140
It's an ultimatum

757
00:33:04.140 --> 00:33:05.140
either to land,

758
00:33:05.140 --> 00:33:06.140
or fly as far away as possible,

759
00:33:06.140 --> 00:33:07.140
and then as fast

760
00:33:07.140 --> 00:33:08.140
as possible, land.

761
00:33:08.140 --> 00:33:10.140
But if it actually looks like this,

762
00:33:10.140 --> 00:33:11.140
then it's no longer good for flying at all.

763
00:33:11.140 --> 00:33:13.140
It's a real outflow,

764
00:33:13.140 --> 00:33:14.140
you can really see,

765
00:33:14.140 --> 00:33:16.140
how it's like a bucket of water being emptied,

766
00:33:16.140 --> 00:33:18.140
with massive cold air being expelled.

767
00:33:18.140 --> 00:33:21.140
And that means a lot of wind.

768
00:33:21.140 --> 00:33:23.490
Then again with radar,

769
00:33:23.490 --> 00:33:24.490
as already mentioned,

770
00:33:24.490 --> 00:33:25.490
it's important

771
00:33:25.490 --> 00:33:26.490
to watch the radar,

772
00:33:26.490 --> 00:33:27.490
to see what's happening.

773
00:33:27.490 --> 00:33:29.490
Watch the clouds in the surroundings,

774
00:33:29.490 --> 00:33:30.490
whether we're under the cloud

775
00:33:30.490 --> 00:33:31.490
or not, how high it is,

776
00:33:31.490 --> 00:33:32.490
also look elsewhere,

777
00:33:32.490 --> 00:33:34.490
maybe the other clouds 50 km away,

778
00:33:34.490 --> 00:33:36.490
and if there's already a huge tower there,

779
00:33:36.490 --> 00:33:37.490
then we know

780
00:33:37.490 --> 00:33:40.520
that maybe the cloud above us isn't much smaller.

781
00:33:40.520 --> 00:33:42.520
So with radar it's really important.

782
00:33:42.520 --> 00:33:43.520
Watch the radar,

783
00:33:43.520 --> 00:33:44.520
that's a good thing,

784
00:33:44.520 --> 00:33:47.520
but also keep watching the clouds back there.

785
00:34:18.160 --> 00:34:20.160
The zones I want to point out here,

786
00:34:20.160 --> 00:34:21.160
the lookouts,

787
00:34:21.160 --> 00:34:23.160
where you can fly in front of the cloud.

788
00:34:23.160 --> 00:34:24.160
But of course with thunderstorms,

789
00:34:24.160 --> 00:34:26.160
really be careful.

790
00:34:26.160 --> 00:34:28.160
It has a lot to do with intuition,

791
00:34:28.160 --> 00:34:30.160
and it's often a game with fire

792
00:34:30.160 --> 00:34:32.580
when it really comes to thunderstorms.

793
00:34:32.580 --> 00:34:33.580
Exactly.

794
00:34:33.580 --> 00:34:39.530
Then we can move to the next important chapter,

795
00:34:39.530 --> 00:34:44.110
the valley wind system.

796
00:34:44.110 --> 00:34:45.110
It's a really important phenomenon,

797
00:34:45.110 --> 00:34:48.110
which by the way happens in all regions,

798
00:34:48.110 --> 00:34:50.110
including the Alps.

799
00:34:50.110 --> 00:34:52.110
And it goes back and forth.

800
00:34:52.110 --> 00:34:55.110
Now we keep tying more things together.

801
00:34:55.110 --> 00:34:57.110
We have solar radiation,

802
00:34:57.110 --> 00:35:02.110
where in mountainous areas much more heat is produced,

803
00:35:02.110 --> 00:35:04.110
or they heat up better,

804
00:35:04.110 --> 00:35:06.110
than the flatlands.

805
00:35:06.110 --> 00:35:07.110
Accordingly,

806
00:35:07.110 --> 00:35:09.110
you get heating around the Alps,

807
00:35:09.110 --> 00:35:11.110
in this case,

808
00:35:11.110 --> 00:35:15.110
a lower air pressure forms during the day.

809
00:35:15.110 --> 00:35:17.110
And you can have air masses,

810
00:35:17.110 --> 00:35:19.110
because pressure always equalises,

811
00:35:19.110 --> 00:35:22.110
lower pressure in the flatlands,

812
00:35:22.110 --> 00:35:25.110
and lower pressure in the mountains.

813
00:35:25.110 --> 00:35:29.110
Accordingly you get equalising flows over the course of the day.

814
00:35:29.110 --> 00:35:30.240
Profile.

815
00:35:30.240 --> 00:35:32.240
Note the cross-section of changes,

816
00:35:32.240 --> 00:35:34.240
with high pressure,

817
00:35:34.240 --> 00:35:36.240
as it cools through isobars.

818
00:35:36.240 --> 00:35:37.240
You can see,

819
00:35:37.240 --> 00:35:38.240
of course it's never quite drawn like this,

820
00:35:38.240 --> 00:35:39.240
in isobars in the cold air.

821
00:35:39.240 --> 00:35:41.240
But at least higher pressure and lower pressure.

822
00:35:41.240 --> 00:35:43.240
But exactly the same weather,

823
00:35:43.240 --> 00:35:44.240
with the pressure equalising,

824
00:35:44.240 --> 00:35:45.240
with the wind system,

825
00:35:45.240 --> 00:35:46.240
that arises.

826
00:35:46.240 --> 00:35:49.300
Accordingly you get equalising flows,

827
00:35:49.300 --> 00:35:51.300
during the day.

828
00:35:51.300 --> 00:35:52.300
It's usually strongest.

829
00:35:52.300 --> 00:35:55.300
From around eleven it starts.

830
00:35:55.300 --> 00:35:59.300
